Drupal is able to authenticate using CrowdID, however the SReg Response is terminated (not even processed) by *openid4java*.

Drupal requires nickname and email:
{code}
[openid.sreg.required] => nickname,email
{code}

Since the authentication works, but the attribute exchange fail, Drupal requests the Email and Nickname in the UI.

Crowd uses the following format for dates in its exports/imports:

{{EEE MMM dd HH:mm:ss Z yyyy}}

Two of these fields, {{EEE}} and {{MMM}}, result in the name of the day and month being output.  These names vary based on the locale, eg in English you may have:

{{Tue Mar 01 12:40:02 +1100 2011}}

but in German it will be:

{{Di Mrz 01 12:40:02 +1100 2011}}

If the locale of the system being imported into is not the same as the locale of the system being exported into, this can cause errors, because the date won't be able to be parsed.  Even using the year number like that will cause problems for locales with different calendars, eg the above date in Thai locale is in the year 2554.  What should be used is the milliseconds since epoch.

Currently, Crowd creates a new User DN using the new *user id* string (same value as the sAMAccountName attribute)

Example for user John Smith:
{code}
CN=jsmith,OU=Users,DC=Domain,DC=com
{code}

However Active Directory uses the First Name concatenated to the Last Name, that in Crowd we parse as the *displayName*.

Example for user John Smith:
{code}
CN=John Smith,OU=Users,DC=Domain,DC=com
{code}

Currently, Crowd is not able to create User DNs in the same format that AD does

On the Crowd screen titled "Help! I forgot my login details", please change the words "in into" to just "in to" in the username field label. So please change this:
{quote}
The username you use to log in into Crowd.
{quote}
to this:
{quote}
The username you use to log in to Crowd.
{quote}

This is the email text in the default template for the "Forgot Username" email message:
{noformat}
Hello $firstname $lastname,

You have requested the username for your email: $email.

Your username is: $username

If you think it was sent incorrectly, please contact one of the administrators at: $admincontact

$deploymenttitle Administrator
{noformat}


Here is an example of an email message sent when there were 2 usernames for a single email address:
{quote}
Hello Admin Administrator,

You have requested the username for your email: smaddox@atlassian.com.

Your username is: admin, arthur

If you think it was sent incorrectly, please contact one of the administrators at: smaddox@atlassian.com

Crowd Administrator
{quote}

Please change the following:
* Change "email" to "email address" in this line:
{noformat}
You have requested the username for your email: $email
{noformat}

* Change "username is" to "username(s) are" in this line:
{noformat}
Your username is:
{noformat}
_It would be even better if we could generate the correct grammar: if there is only one username, then send "username is" and if there are two or more usernames, then send "usernames are". Is that possible, given that this is the default template?_

* Change "it" to "this email" in this line:
{noformat}
If you think it was sent incorrectly,...
{noformat}

When you follow the new 'forgot password' workflow, you eventually get a message that says:
{quote}
*Reset Password* 
Your new password is on the way!
{quote}


Instead, it should say:
{quote}
*Reset Password* 
An email message is on the way! It contains a unique, random URL. Click the link in the email message or copy it to your browser address bar. The link leads to a page where you can choose your new password.
{quote}

In the Apache::CrowdAuthz file, the Crowd Connector fails to parse repository paths with spaces. Example:
{code}
[/root/repository/xxx yyy]
{code}

Current Regex:
{code}
^\s*\[(\S+)\]\s*$
{code}
Fix:
{code}
^\s*\[([^\]]*)\]\s*$
{code}

Important: This was not fixed by http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/CWD-820

